They brought the fire under control without major injuries, but residents of 6 and 10 Marie St. were especially shaken up.\r\n\r\n"For those neighbors, the threat had long been apparent: nearby residents told the Boston Globe’s Aimee Ortiz that the house had been unoccupied for at least nine years. Google Street View’s entry for the property, taken in 2014, shows the house boarded, up with the exterior in poor condition.\r\n\r\n"Firefighters, however, began by sweeping for residents: “You have to look under beds, you have to look in closets…and then eventually somebody told them, ‘oh, that’s a vacant building,’ but you don’t know that when you show up,” a Boston Fire Department spokesman told the Globe.\r\n\r\n"One goal of this analysis is to show how data collected by other City of Boston agencies could assist the Fire Department in situations like these. Just a few years of citizen reports and Inspectional Services Departments records, all captured by the city’s 311 database, would have been enough to flag 8 Marie St. as potentially vacant. Other records, like utility billing records, could have provided even more precise evidence. The department could even try a “civic hack” like Louisville, KY, which uses inexpensive, locally-developed smoke alarm sensors to catch fires early in abandoned properties.\r\n\r\n"But the bigger problem has no quick fix. My main objective here is to highlight the need for citywide focus on houses like 8 Marie St. These are the “problem properties” that degrade neighborhoods–sometimes slowly, and sometimes quickly. Between 2012 and 2016, citizens complained to the city 15 times about unsafe conditions at 8 Marie St, according to 311 records. While causes of this fire haven’t been determined, vacant properties tend to attract squatters and other illicit activities that can contribute to fire risk; they may also be targets for arson. In this case, neighbors’ safety concerns were confirmed.\r\n\r\n"Business as usual won’t solve these problems. Since 2012, the Inspectional Services Department issued at least five tickets for unsafe structural conditions at 8 Marie St. When a landlord won’t comply, the process for rehabilitating a problem property is long and costly. Boston, to its advantage, has power under 2013’s Rental Registration and Inspection Ordinance to crack down on rental properties that aren’t up to code.\r\n\r\n"While inspecting every eligible property is a tall order, not every property poses the same safety risk. That’s the focus of this analysis."\r\n\r\n[Source code is available on GitHub.](https://github.com/JonJayHub/Fire-Proof)', 'title': 'Fire-Proof Boston Housing', 'showcase_notes_formatted': '<p><strong>Fire-Proof Boston Housing</strong></p>\n<p><em>This project, from <a href="https://twitter.com/jonjaytweets">Jon Jay</a>, was a winner in Track 4 (Identifying Fire Risks) of our 2017 Open Data Challenge and one of the audience-chosen overall winners at the challenge\'s showcase event.</em></p>\n<p>"This analysis is dedicated to the 17 Dorchester residents displaced from their homes by an early-morning fire Sunday, April 23, 2017.</p>\n<p>"The six-alarm blaze started at 8 Marie St, a three-family house overlooking Ronan Park, sometime before 4 a.m. Flames leapt to neighboring houses on either side; the heat alone melted siding on other nearby properties. 80 firefighters were called in. They brought the fire under control without major injuries, but residents of 6 and 10 Marie St. were especially shaken up.</p>\n<p>"For those neighbors, the threat had long been apparent: nearby residents told the Boston Globe’s Aimee Ortiz that the house had been unoccupied for at least nine years. Google Street View’s entry for the property, taken in 2014, shows the house boarded, up with the exterior in poor condition.</p>\n<p>"Firefighters, however, began by sweeping for residents: “You have to look under beds, you have to look in closets…and then eventually somebody told them, ‘oh, that’s a vacant building,’ but you don’t know that when you show up,” a Boston Fire Department spokesman told the Globe.</p>\n<p>"One goal of this analysis is to show how data collected by other City of Boston agencies could assist the Fire Department in situations like these. Just a few years of citizen reports and Inspectional Services Departments records, all captured by the city’s 311 database, would have been enough to flag 8 Marie St. as potentially vacant. Other records, like utility billing records, could have provided even more precise evidence. The department could even try a “civic hack” like Louisville, KY, which uses inexpensive, locally-developed smoke alarm sensors to catch fires early in abandoned properties.</p>\n<p>"But the bigger problem has no quick fix. My main objective here is to highlight the need for citywide focus on houses like 8 Marie St. These are the “problem properties” that degrade neighborhoods–sometimes slowly, and sometimes quickly. Between 2012 and 2016, citizens complained to the city 15 times about unsafe conditions at 8 Marie St, according to 311 records. While causes of this fire haven’t been determined, vacant properties tend to attract squatters and other illicit activities that can contribute to fire risk; they may also be targets for arson. In this case, neighbors’ safety concerns were confirmed.</p>\n<p>"Business as usual won’t solve these problems. Since 2012, the Inspectional Services Department issued at least five tickets for unsafe structural conditions at 8 Marie St. When a landlord won’t comply, the process for rehabilitating a problem property is long and costly. Boston, to its advantage, has power under 2013’s Rental Registration and Inspection Ordinance to crack down on rental properties that aren’t up to code.</p>\n<p>"While inspecting every eligible property is a tall order, not every property poses the same safety risk. That’s the focus of this analysis."</p>\n<p><a href="https://github.com/JonJayHub/Fire-Proof">Source code is available on GitHub.</a></p>', 'image_url': '2017-05-12-185233.067111Screen-Shot-2017-05-12-at-2.53.49-PM.png', 'revision_id': 'dac8a5ef-abde-4918-8bc9-ddbb1e6070b0', 'redirect_link': False}}

See the [Imagine Boston 2030 Goals](http://imagine.boston.gov/about/#goals) for further information.\r\n\r\nThe metrics dashboard features 14 metrics that will be evaluated on a yearly basis to measure and track the City’s overall progress towards achieving the plan’s goals. The metrics reflect Boston’s data driven approach to guiding long-term growth to boost quality of life, equity and resilience in every neighborhood across Boston. The dashboard allows users to interact with data available on historic trends, current benchmarks and how we will achieve the goals laid out in the plan.\r\n\r\nThe 14 established metrics are reflective of the five overarching goals established by residents through the Imagine Boston 2030 engagement process. More than 15,000 residents contributed to inform the following goals: (1) encourage affordability, reduce displacement, and improve quality of life, (2) increase access to opportunity, (3) drive inclusive economic growth, (4) promote a healthy environment and prepare for climate change, and (5) invest in open space, arts & culture, transportation, and infrastructure. The metrics track progress in the following areas: housing cost burden, premature mortality, walkability, safety, wealth gap disparity, childhood poverty, education, job creation, energy emissions, climate change, parks quality, commute modes, and arts and culture.\r\n\r\n*The data included in this dashboard includes a mix of City, State, and Federal, and private-sector datasets. See the <a href="http://imagine.boston.gov/about/#goals">Imagine Boston 2030 Goals</a> for further information.</p>\n<p>The metrics dashboard features 14 metrics that will be evaluated on a yearly basis to measure and track the City’s overall progress towards achieving the plan’s goals. The metrics reflect Boston’s data driven approach to guiding long-term growth to boost quality of life, equity and resilience in every neighborhood across Boston. The dashboard allows users to interact with data available on historic trends, current benchmarks and how we will achieve the goals laid out in the plan.</p>\n<p>The 14 established metrics are reflective of the five overarching goals established by residents through the Imagine Boston 2030 engagement process. More than 15,000 residents contributed to inform the following goals: (1) encourage affordability, reduce displacement, and improve quality of life, (2) increase access to opportunity, (3) drive inclusive economic growth, (4) promote a healthy environment and prepare for climate change, and (5) invest in open space, arts &amp; culture, transportation, and infrastructure. The metrics track progress in the following areas: housing cost burden, premature mortality, walkability, safety, wealth gap disparity, childhood poverty, education, job creation, energy emissions, climate change, parks quality, commute modes, and arts and culture.</p>\n<p><em>The data included in this dashboard includes a mix of City, State, and Federal, and private-sector datasets. Specific sources are listed alongside their respective analyses. Some of the City data referenced in this dashboard is not yet available on Analyze Boston but will be added in the future. We will update this page as more of the included data is made available on this site.</em></p>', 'image_url': '2017-09-19-210104.375888Capture.PNG', 'revision_id': 'ccb95781-c7cd-495a-b9ef-cb730dbc22b1', 'redirect_link': False}}

The City’s recurring revenue budget can be divided into four categories: Property Tax (72% of total revenue), State Aid (12%), Departmental Revenue (9%) and Excise (6%). Non-recurring revenue accounts for 1% of the City's total revenue budget.\r\n\r\nFor more information on the City of Boston Budget please see the interactive web application at budget.boston.gov. {'help': 'https://data.boston.gov/api/3/action/help_show?name=package_show', 'success': True, 'result': {'notes_translated': {'en': "[**Click here to check Short-Term Rental Eligibility**](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/short-term-rental-eligibility/resource/83621b97-9a00-4aa7-bf43-28cae04969d4)  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\nBoston's ordinance on short-term rentals is designed to incorporate the growth of the home-share industry into the City's work to create affordable housing for all residents. We want to preserve housing for residents while allowing Bostonians to benefit from this new industry. Starting on on January 1, 2019, short-term rentals in Boston will need to [register with the City of Boston](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals).\r\n\r\nEligibility for every unit in the City of Boston is dependant on the following six criteria:\r\n\r\n* No affordability covenant restrictions\r\n* Compliance with housing laws and codes\r\n* No violations of laws regarding short-term rental use\r\n* Owner occupied\r\n* Two- or three-family dwelling\r\n* Residential use classification\r\n\r\nThe Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset leverages information, wherever possible, about these criteria. For additional details and information about these criteria, please visit [https://www.boston.gov/short-term-rentals](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals). \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n## ABOUT THIS DATASET\r\n\r\nIn June 2018, a citywide ordinance established new guidelines and regulations for short-term rentals in Boston. Registration opened January 1, 2019. The Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset was created to help residents, landlords, and City officials determine whether a property is eligible to be registered as a short-term rental.\r\n\r\nThe Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset currently joins data from the following datasets and is refreshed nightly:\r\n\r\n* [Live Street Address Management (SAM) Addresses](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/live-street-address-management-sam-addresses).  \r\n* [Assessing Online](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/assessing-online).  \r\n* [Building and Property Violations](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/building-and-property-violations1)   \r\n* [Problem Properties](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1V0ZOge7yxbaQmlcuiZX20Sy2Mykrm6cbGVdpjWC_TNY/edit#gid=0)  \r\n* Income-Restricted Properties  \r\n* STR Registration Data  \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n## HOW TO DETERMINE ELIGIBILITY FOR SHORT-TERM RENTAL REGISTRATION\r\n\r\n1. [** Open**](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/short-term-rental-eligibility/resource/83621b97-9a00-4aa7-bf43-28cae04969d4) the Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset.   In the dataset's search bar, **enter the address** of the property you are seeking to register. \r\n\r\n2. Find the **row** containing the correct **address and unit** of the property you are seeking. This is the information we have for your unit.\r\n\r\n3. Look at the columns marked as “Home-Share Eligible,” “Limited-Share Eligible,” and “Owner-Adjacent Eligible.”  \r\n    * A **“yes”** under any of these columns means **your unit IS eligible** for registration under that short-term rental type. [Click here for a description of short-term rental types.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-types) \r\n    * A **“no”** under any of these columns means **your unit is NOT eligible** for registration under that short-term rental type. [Click here for a description of short-term rental types.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-types)  \r\n\r\n4. If your unit has a **“yes”** under “Home-Share Eligible,” “Limited-Share Eligible,” or “Owner-Adjacent Eligible,” you can [register your unit here](http://boston.gov/short-term-rentals).\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n## WHY IS MY UNIT LISTED AS “NOT ELIGIBLE”?\r\n\r\nIf you find that your unit is listed as **NOT eligible**, and you would like to understand more about why, you can use the Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset to learn more. The following columns measure each of the six eligibility criteria in the following ways:\r\n\r\n1.  No affordability covenant restrictions\r\n\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Income Restricted”** column tells you that the unit is marked as **income restricted** and is NOT eligible.   \r\n<br/>\r\n    * The **“Income Restricted”** column measures whether the unit is subject to an **affordability covenant**, as reported by the Department of Neighborhood Development and/or the Boston Planning and Development Agency.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * For questions about **affordability covenants**, contact the [Department of Neighborhood Development.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-development)  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n2. Compliance with housing laws and codes  \r\n\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Problem Properties”** column tells you that this unit is considered a “Problem Property” by the Problem Properties Task Force and is NOT eligible.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * Learn more about how “Problem Properties” are defined [here.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services/problem-properties-boston)  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Problem Property Owner”** column tells you that the owner of this unit also owns a “Problem Property,” as reported by the Problem Properties Task Force.  \r\n<br/> \r\n    * Owners with **any properties designated as a Problem Property** are NOT eligible.    \r\n<br/>\r\n    * No unit owned by the owner of a “Problem Property” may register a short-term rental.   \r\n<br/> \r\n    * Learn more about how “Problem Properties” are defined [__here.__](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services/problem-properties-boston)  \r\n<br/>\r\n    *  The **“Open Violation Count”** column tells you how many open violations the unit has. Units with **any open** violations are NOT eligible. Violations counted include: violations of the sanitary, building, zoning, and fire code; stop work orders; and abatement orders.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * NOTE: Violations **written before 1/1/19** that are **still open** will make a unit NOT eligible **until these violations are resolved**.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * If your unit has an open violation, visit these links to [**appeal your violation(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-appeal-code-violation) or [**pay your code violation fine(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-pay-fine-code-violation).  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * The **“Violations in the Last 6 Months”** column tells you how many violations the unit has received in the last six months. Units with **three or more** violations, whether open or closed, are NOT eligible.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * NOTE: Only violations written **on or after 1/1/19** will count against this criteria.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * If your unit has an open violation, visit these links to [**appeal your violation(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-appeal-code-violation) or [**pay your code violation fine(s).**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-pay-fine-code-violation)  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * How to comply with housing laws and codes:  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * **Have an open violation?** Visit these links to [**appeal your violation(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-appeal-code-violation) or [**pay your code violation fine(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-pay-fine-code-violation).  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * **Have questions about problem properties?** Visit Neighborhood Service’s [Problem Properties](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services/problem-properties-boston) site.  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n3. No violations of laws regarding short-term rental use\r\n\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Legally Restricted”** column tells you that there is a **complaint against the unit** that finds \r\n\r\n        *  A legal restriction that prohibits the use of the unit as a Short-Term Rental under local, state, or federal law, OR  \r\n\r\n        * legal restriction that prohibits the use of the unit as a Short-Term Rental under condominium bylaws.  \r\n\r\n        * Units with legal restrictions found upon investigation are NOT eligible.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If the investigation of a complaint against the unit yields restrictions of the nature detailed above, we will mark the unit with a “yes” in this column. Until such complaint-based investigations begin, all units are marked with “no.”  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * NOTE: Currently no units have a “legally restricted” designation.  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n4. Owner-occupied\r\n\r\n    * A **“no”** in the **“Unit Owner-Occupied”** column tells you that there is **NO [Residential Tax Exemption](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing/filing-property-tax-exemption#nav-1149644700) filed** for that unit via the Assessing Department, and that unit is automatically categorized as NOT eligible for the following [Short-Term Rental types](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-types):\r\n\r\n        * Home-Share  \r\n        * Limited-Share  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * [Residential Tax Exemption](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing/filing-property-tax-exemption#nav-1149644700) **indicates** that a unit is owner-occupied and generates a “yes” in the “Unit Owner-Occupied” column.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * Owners are **not required** to file a Residential Tax Exemption in order to be eligible to register a unit as a Short-Term Rental.  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n        * If you would like to apply for Residential Tax Exemption, you can [apply here](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing/how-file-residential-exemption).  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you are the owner-occupant of a unit and you have not filed for Residential Tax Exemption, you can still register your unit by proving owner-occupancy. \r\n<br/>\r\n        * It is recommended that you [submit proof of residency](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-eligibility-criteria) in your short-term rental registration application to expedite the process of proving owner-occupancy (see “Primary Residence Evidence” section).\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n    * **“Building Owner-Occupied”** measures whether the building has a single owner AND is owner occupied. A “no” in this column indicates that the unit is NOT eligible for an owner-adjacent short-term rental.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you believe your building occupancy data is incorrect, please contact the [Assessing Department](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing).  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n5. Two- or three-family dwelling\r\n\r\n    * The **“Units in Building”** column tells you how many units are in the building. Owner-Adjacent units are only allowed in two- to three-family buildings; therefore, **four or more** units in this column will mark the unit as NOT eligible for an Owner-Adjacent Short-Term Rental.\r\n\r\n    * A **“no”** in the **“Building Single Owner”** column tells you that the owner of this unit **does not own the entire building** and is NOT eligible for an Owner-Adjacent Short-Term Rental.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you believe your building occupancy data is incorrect, please contact the [Assessing Department](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing).  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n6. Residential use classification\r\n\r\n    * The Short Term Rental Eligibility Dataset only displays units that are designated for residential use. Units designated for residential use will have one of the following [land use codes](https://www.cityofboston.gov/assessing/pdfs/land_use_codes.pdf):  \r\n\r\n           * A  \r\n           * CD  \r\n           * RC  \r\n           * R1  \r\n           * R2  \r\n           * R3  \r\n           * R4  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you believe your building occupancy data is incorrect, please contact the [Assessing Department](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing).  \r\n        \r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nVisit this site for more information on [**unit eligibility criteria**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-eligibility-criteria)."}, 'owner_org': '80644104-7cff-4322-b2a3-33466d5e98bb', 'maintainer': None, 'contact_point_phone': '', 'license_id': 'notspecified', 'publisher': 'Department of Innovation and Technology', 'name': 'short-term-rental-eligibility', 'isopen': False, 'accrual_periodicity': 'R/P1D', 'notes': "[**Click here to check Short-Term Rental Eligibility**](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/short-term-rental-eligibility/resource/83621b97-9a00-4aa7-bf43-28cae04969d4)  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\nBoston's ordinance on short-term rentals is designed to incorporate the growth of the home-share industry into the City's work to create affordable housing for all residents. We want to preserve housing for residents while allowing Bostonians to benefit from this new industry. Starting on on January 1, 2019, short-term rentals in Boston will need to [register with the City of Boston](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals).\r\n\r\nEligibility for every unit in the City of Boston is dependant on the following six criteria:\r\n\r\n* No affordability covenant restrictions\r\n* Compliance with housing laws and codes\r\n* No violations of laws regarding short-term rental use\r\n* Owner occupied\r\n* Two- or three-family dwelling\r\n* Residential use classification\r\n\r\nThe Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset leverages information, wherever possible, about these criteria. For additional details and information about these criteria, please visit [https://www.boston.gov/short-term-rentals](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals). \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n## ABOUT THIS DATASET\r\n\r\nIn June 2018, a citywide ordinance established new guidelines and regulations for short-term rentals in Boston. Registration opened January 1, 2019. The Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset was created to help residents, landlords, and City officials determine whether a property is eligible to be registered as a short-term rental.\r\n\r\nThe Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset currently joins data from the following datasets and is refreshed nightly:\r\n\r\n* [Live Street Address Management (SAM) Addresses](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/live-street-address-management-sam-addresses).  \r\n* [Assessing Online](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/assessing-online).  \r\n* [Building and Property Violations](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/building-and-property-violations1)   \r\n* [Problem Properties](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1V0ZOge7yxbaQmlcuiZX20Sy2Mykrm6cbGVdpjWC_TNY/edit#gid=0)  \r\n* Income-Restricted Properties  \r\n* STR Registration Data  \r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n## HOW TO DETERMINE ELIGIBILITY FOR SHORT-TERM RENTAL REGISTRATION\r\n\r\n1. [** Open**](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/short-term-rental-eligibility/resource/83621b97-9a00-4aa7-bf43-28cae04969d4) the Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset.   In the dataset's search bar, **enter the address** of the property you are seeking to register. \r\n\r\n2. Find the **row** containing the correct **address and unit** of the property you are seeking. This is the information we have for your unit.\r\n\r\n3. Look at the columns marked as “Home-Share Eligible,” “Limited-Share Eligible,” and “Owner-Adjacent Eligible.”  \r\n    * A **“yes”** under any of these columns means **your unit IS eligible** for registration under that short-term rental type. [Click here for a description of short-term rental types.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-types) \r\n    * A **“no”** under any of these columns means **your unit is NOT eligible** for registration under that short-term rental type. [Click here for a description of short-term rental types.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-types)  \r\n\r\n4. If your unit has a **“yes”** under “Home-Share Eligible,” “Limited-Share Eligible,” or “Owner-Adjacent Eligible,” you can [register your unit here](http://boston.gov/short-term-rentals).\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n## WHY IS MY UNIT LISTED AS “NOT ELIGIBLE”?\r\n\r\nIf you find that your unit is listed as **NOT eligible**, and you would like to understand more about why, you can use the Short-Term Rental Eligibility Dataset to learn more. The following columns measure each of the six eligibility criteria in the following ways:\r\n\r\n1.  No affordability covenant restrictions\r\n\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Income Restricted”** column tells you that the unit is marked as **income restricted** and is NOT eligible.   \r\n<br/>\r\n    * The **“Income Restricted”** column measures whether the unit is subject to an **affordability covenant**, as reported by the Department of Neighborhood Development and/or the Boston Planning and Development Agency.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * For questions about **affordability covenants**, contact the [Department of Neighborhood Development.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-development)  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n2. Compliance with housing laws and codes  \r\n\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Problem Properties”** column tells you that this unit is considered a “Problem Property” by the Problem Properties Task Force and is NOT eligible.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * Learn more about how “Problem Properties” are defined [here.](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services/problem-properties-boston)  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Problem Property Owner”** column tells you that the owner of this unit also owns a “Problem Property,” as reported by the Problem Properties Task Force.  \r\n<br/> \r\n    * Owners with **any properties designated as a Problem Property** are NOT eligible.    \r\n<br/>\r\n    * No unit owned by the owner of a “Problem Property” may register a short-term rental.   \r\n<br/> \r\n    * Learn more about how “Problem Properties” are defined [__here.__](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services/problem-properties-boston)  \r\n<br/>\r\n    *  The **“Open Violation Count”** column tells you how many open violations the unit has. Units with **any open** violations are NOT eligible. Violations counted include: violations of the sanitary, building, zoning, and fire code; stop work orders; and abatement orders.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * NOTE: Violations **written before 1/1/19** that are **still open** will make a unit NOT eligible **until these violations are resolved**.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * If your unit has an open violation, visit these links to [**appeal your violation(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-appeal-code-violation) or [**pay your code violation fine(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-pay-fine-code-violation).  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * The **“Violations in the Last 6 Months”** column tells you how many violations the unit has received in the last six months. Units with **three or more** violations, whether open or closed, are NOT eligible.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * NOTE: Only violations written **on or after 1/1/19** will count against this criteria.  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * If your unit has an open violation, visit these links to [**appeal your violation(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-appeal-code-violation) or [**pay your code violation fine(s).**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-pay-fine-code-violation)  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * How to comply with housing laws and codes:  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * **Have an open violation?** Visit these links to [**appeal your violation(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-appeal-code-violation) or [**pay your code violation fine(s)**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-works/how-pay-fine-code-violation).  \r\n<br/>\r\n    * **Have questions about problem properties?** Visit Neighborhood Service’s [Problem Properties](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services/problem-properties-boston) site.  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n3. No violations of laws regarding short-term rental use\r\n\r\n    * A **“yes”** in the **“Legally Restricted”** column tells you that there is a **complaint against the unit** that finds \r\n\r\n        *  A legal restriction that prohibits the use of the unit as a Short-Term Rental under local, state, or federal law, OR  \r\n\r\n        * legal restriction that prohibits the use of the unit as a Short-Term Rental under condominium bylaws.  \r\n\r\n        * Units with legal restrictions found upon investigation are NOT eligible.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If the investigation of a complaint against the unit yields restrictions of the nature detailed above, we will mark the unit with a “yes” in this column. Until such complaint-based investigations begin, all units are marked with “no.”  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * NOTE: Currently no units have a “legally restricted” designation.  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n4. Owner-occupied\r\n\r\n    * A **“no”** in the **“Unit Owner-Occupied”** column tells you that there is **NO [Residential Tax Exemption](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing/filing-property-tax-exemption#nav-1149644700) filed** for that unit via the Assessing Department, and that unit is automatically categorized as NOT eligible for the following [Short-Term Rental types](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-types):\r\n\r\n        * Home-Share  \r\n        * Limited-Share  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * [Residential Tax Exemption](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing/filing-property-tax-exemption#nav-1149644700) **indicates** that a unit is owner-occupied and generates a “yes” in the “Unit Owner-Occupied” column.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * Owners are **not required** to file a Residential Tax Exemption in order to be eligible to register a unit as a Short-Term Rental.  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n        * If you would like to apply for Residential Tax Exemption, you can [apply here](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing/how-file-residential-exemption).  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you are the owner-occupant of a unit and you have not filed for Residential Tax Exemption, you can still register your unit by proving owner-occupancy. \r\n<br/>\r\n        * It is recommended that you [submit proof of residency](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-eligibility-criteria) in your short-term rental registration application to expedite the process of proving owner-occupancy (see “Primary Residence Evidence” section).\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n    * **“Building Owner-Occupied”** measures whether the building has a single owner AND is owner occupied. A “no” in this column indicates that the unit is NOT eligible for an owner-adjacent short-term rental.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you believe your building occupancy data is incorrect, please contact the [Assessing Department](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing).  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n5. Two- or three-family dwelling\r\n\r\n    * The **“Units in Building”** column tells you how many units are in the building. Owner-Adjacent units are only allowed in two- to three-family buildings; therefore, **four or more** units in this column will mark the unit as NOT eligible for an Owner-Adjacent Short-Term Rental.\r\n\r\n    * A **“no”** in the **“Building Single Owner”** column tells you that the owner of this unit **does not own the entire building** and is NOT eligible for an Owner-Adjacent Short-Term Rental.  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you believe your building occupancy data is incorrect, please contact the [Assessing Department](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing).  \r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n6. Residential use classification\r\n\r\n    * The Short Term Rental Eligibility Dataset only displays units that are designated for residential use. Units designated for residential use will have one of the following [land use codes](https://www.cityofboston.gov/assessing/pdfs/land_use_codes.pdf):  \r\n\r\n           * A  \r\n           * CD  \r\n           * RC  \r\n           * R1  \r\n           * R2  \r\n           * R3  \r\n           * R4  \r\n<br/>\r\n        * If you believe your building occupancy data is incorrect, please contact the [Assessing Department](https://www.boston.gov/departments/assessing).  \r\n        \r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nVisit this site for more information on [**unit eligibility criteria**](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/short-term-rentals#unit-eligibility-criteria).", 'license_title': 'License not specified', 'url': '', 'btype': ['tabular'], 'organization': {'description': 'We manage the City’s websites and technologies, like the BOS:311 app, that are focused on service delivery. Various types of counts: Turning Movement Counts, Automated Traffic Recordings, Pedestrian Counts, Delay Studies, and Gap Studies.\r\n\r\n~__Turning Movement Counts (TMC)__ present the number of motor vehicles, pedestrians, and cyclists passing through the particular intersection. Specific movements and crossings are recorded for all street approaches involved with the intersection. This data is used in traffic signal retiming programs and for signal requests.  Counts are typically conducted for 2-, 4-, 11-, and 12-Hr periods.\r\n\r\n~__Automated Traffic Recordings (ATR)__ record the volume of motor vehicles traveling along a particular road, measures of travel speeds, and approximations of the class of the vehicles (motorcycle, 2-axle, large box truck, bus, etc).  This type of count is conducted only along a street link/corridor, to gather data between two intersections or points of interest.  This data is used in travel studies, as well as to review concerns about street use, speeding, and capacity. Counts are typically conducted for 12- & 24-Hr periods.\r\n\r\n~__Pedestrian Counts (PED)__ record the volume of individual persons crossing a given street, whether at an existing intersection or a mid-block crossing.  This data is used to review concerns about crossing safety, as well as for access analysis for points of interest.   Counts are typically conducted for 2-, 4-, 11-, and 12-Hr periods.\r\n\r\n~__Delay Studies (DEL)__ measure the delay experienced by motor vehicles due to the effects of congestion.  Counts are typically conducted for a 1-Hr period at a given intersection or point of intersecting vehicular traffic.\r\n\r\n~__Gap Studies (GAP)__ record the number of gaps which are typically present between groups of vehicles traveling through an intersection or past a point on a street.  This data is used to assess opportunities for pedestrians to cross the street and for analyses on vehicular “platooning”. {'help': 'https://data.boston.gov/api/3/action/help_show?name=package_show', 'success': True, 'result': {'notes_translated': {'en': '### DATASET CONTEXT\r\nTransportation Access Plan Agreements (TAPAs) are legal documents between large developments and the Boston Transportation Department. Large developments are any development greater than 50,000 square feet. The development review process requires developers to evaluate transportation conditions and mitigate their developments’ impacts on the transportation network. The final agreement specifies commitments that will reduce a development’s transportation impacts. These commitments can include improvements such as installing traffic signals, bike lanes, and adopting commuter incentives to reduce driving. Developments under 50,000 square feet are not usually required to submit a TAPA.\r\n\r\n### ABOUT THIS DATASET\r\nThis dataset includes __all known, executed__ TAPAs for large developments over 50,000 sq ft from 1986 to the present day. Each datapoint includes a PDF of the original executed TAPA. TAPAs do not verify what is actually built, only what was approved by the Boston Transportation Department at the date of execution. {'help': 'https://data.boston.gov/api/3/action/help_show?name=package_show', 'success': True, 'result': {'notes_translated': {'en': '### TO VIEW A GLOSSARY OF TERMS FOR THE DIRECTORY - [CLICK HERE](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/zoning-board-of-appeal-tracker/resource/e11dcfa5-6f6f-4999-abc3-741f53c6731f)\r\n \r\n\r\n### WHAT IS THIS TRACKER FOR?\r\nThe City of Boston is committed to increasing transparency in the processes around the Zoning Board of Appeal (ZBA). The Inspectional Services Department (ISD) at the City is tasked with ensuring compliance with the zoning code. If an application for a permit is refused because of a zoning violation, applicants are able to appeal the decision to the ZBA and ask for an exception, sometimes known as a “variance.” If the ZBA grants relief, then the appellant is able to continue with the process of obtaining a permit.  \r\n\r\nIn order to provide greater transparency in the ZBA process, the City of Boston Zoning Board of Appeal tracker is now available on Analyze Boston. Each record in this tracker represents an appeal of a denied permit application; the original permit application is known as the “parent application.” To find out more information about the original permit application, visit our [Permit Finder tool](https://permitfinder.boston.gov/).  To view a map of this data, visit our [ZBA Tracker Map Tool](https://www.boston.gov/appeal-tracker).\r\n\r\n__To learn more about the ZBA process and how to file an appeal, [visit our website](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/how-file-appeal-zoning-board#start-the-appeal-process).__ \r\n   \r\n  \r\n\r\n### WHAT DOES EACH STATUS MEAN?\r\n__Appeal Submitted__ - indicates that an appeal of a zoning refusal was successfully submitted into ISD’s tracking system, either in-person at ISD (1010 Massachusetts Ave.) or through the online application portal.\r\n\r\n_More Information:_ \r\n\r\n* For detailed information on how to file an appeal, see [this page](http://boston.gov/zba-appeal) on the ISD website. \r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n\r\n* The appeal will undergo an initial review by City staff to ensure that all necessary information and \r\n    documentation has been included.\r\n* The appellant must pay a fee.\r\n  \r\n\r\n__Community Process__ - indicates that City staff have completed their review and signed off for the appeal process to move onto getting community feedback.  \r\n\r\n_Contact Information:_\r\n\r\n* Use the link below to find the Neighborhood Liaison from the Office of Neighborhood Services for the application’s location.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_    \r\n\r\n* The appellant will work with the Mayor’s [Office of Neighborhood Services](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services) to engage with people who own adjacent properties, members of the local community, and other relevant stakeholders.  \r\n\r\n* Depending on the type of project, the [Boston Planning and Development Agency](http://www.bostonplans.org/zoning/zoning-board-of-appeals) may also [conduct a review](http://www.bostonplans.org/getattachment/9b57370e-5a54-4d8d-b275-b93e1d7d42e1).  \r\n  \r\n \r\n__[Hearing Scheduled](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal)__ - indicates that the appeal has been scheduled for a committee or subcommittee meeting of the ZBA. For this to take place, the Mayor’s Office of Neighborhood Services has notified ISD that the appellant has adequately engaged with the community that would be affected, should the zoning relief be granted.  \r\n\r\n_Attendance Information:_\r\n\r\n* View a schedule of hearings at the ZBA [webpage](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal#UpcomingHearings). Select an Upcoming Hearing to find the list of topics and how to attend.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n \r\n* The appellant will attend the hearing in person (or through the virtual meeting). The appellant will provide the ZBA with reasons why an exception or variance to the zoning code should be granted and answer any questions from the ZBA.  \r\n\r\n* At the hearing, members of the public will be able to testify in support or against the appeal.  \r\n\r\n* The ZBA will discuss the appeal and vote to approve or deny.  \r\n\r\n_Alternatively:_  \r\n\r\n* The appellant can request a deferral; if allowed by the ZBA, during the hearing the appeal will receive a new hearing date.  \r\n\r\n* The appellant can withdraw the application; if allowed by the ZBA, it can be withdrawn without prejudice.  \r\n\r\n__Hearing Rescheduled__ - indicates that the appeal’s scheduled committee meeting has been changed. This can happen for several reasons. For example, the appellant can request a deferral if they need more time to complete or update plans, or the board can defer an appeal if a quorum isn’t present (perhaps due to a recusal). A request for deferral is approved by the board, which also selects a new hearing date.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_\r\n\r\n* Same as Hearing Scheduled above.\r\n\r\n\r\n__Hearing Concluded__ - indicates that the hearing has taken place. The appeal could have been approved, denied, deferred, or withdrawn, with or without additional requirements.  \r\n\r\n_Additional Information:_\r\n\r\n* Meeting minutes from each committee meeting are available to download from the ZBA [webpage](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal).\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n\r\n* The ZBA Executive Secretary finalizes the Board’s decision in writing or the appellant’s attorney submits a finalized decision for ISD Legal Team review.  \r\n  \r\n\r\n__[ZBA Decision Finalized](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal-decisions)__ - indicates the date on the ZBA’s written decision letter. The decision is listed under the ‘result’ field.  \r\n \r\n_Next steps:_    \r\n\r\n*  Neighboring property owners are notified of the decision shortly after this date  \r\n\r\n* Beginning on the Final Decision Date, neighboring property owners and other involved parties who disagree with the ZBA’s decision have twenty days to file an appeal in Suffolk County Superior Court or Boston Housing Court. (For detailed information on the Zoning Commission and appeal process, please refer to Chapter 665 of the Acts of 1956, available [here](https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2020/02/Zoning%20Commission.pdf))  \r\n  \r\n\r\n__Appeal Closed__ - indicates the appeal’s outcome has been finalized and the twenty day Appeal period has ended.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n\r\n* Depending on the ZBA decision, the appellant may or may not be able to continue the process for seeking the permit for which zoning relief was requested.  \r\n\r\n* If the ZBA approved or sustained with proviso, the appellant must take additional steps before continuing the permitting process.  \r\n\r\n### WHAT DOES EACH RESULT MEAN?  \r\n__Approved__ - means the zoning relief requested has been granted.  \r\n\r\n__Approved with Proviso__ - means the zoning relief requested has been granted, with some conditions that must be fulfilled before the permitting process can continue. These conditions will be detailed in the written decision of the ZBA. Examples of such conditions could include: having the Boston Planning and Development Agency review updated plans; submitting more detailed plans; or obtaining additional engineer reports.  \r\n\r\n__Denied__ - means the zoning relief requested was not granted. The appellant must wait a year before submitting a new appeal on a project for the same site.   \r\n\r\n__Denied without Prejudice__ - means the zoning relief requested was not granted. However, the appellant only has to wait thirty days before submitting an appeal on a new project at the same site.  \r\n   \r\n__Withdrawn__ - means the appellant has chosen to remove the appeal from the ZBA’s consideration. The appellant does not have to wait a year to appeal the same zoning violations.    \r\n\r\n_Note: If there is no result listed, it means that the ZBA has not issued its final written decision on the appeal. This may be the case even for appeals that have been heard by the ZBA._  \r\n \r\n\r\n### HOW DO I USE THIS TRACKER?  \r\nThis tracker is designed for members of the public and City of Boston employees to be able to quickly search for a specific appeal that has been submitted to the ZBA, or to search for appeals based on criteria such as location or primary contact, in order to identify the status of the appeal. \r\n \r\nBelow, under the "Data and Resources" header, you will see the "Zoning Board of Appeal Tracker" dataset:\r\n \r\n* To __look__ at the directory - click the "Preview" button and you will be taken to a spreadsheet-like view of the directory data.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __expand__ the number of applications available to scroll through, click the "Show _ Entries" drop down at the top left of the data table and select your desired number. Alternatively, you can scroll to the bottom right of the dataset and select your desired page number.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __search__ the tracker - use the search box to the top right of the data table to search for any keyword in the dataset. For example, if you are looking for a certain contact, type the name into the search box and see what comes back.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __filter__ the data, click the blue "Add Filter" link at the top left of the data table, select the field you would like to filter on, and select the corresponding value of that field that you would like to display. For example - if you wanted to show applications for properties in Charlestown, you would click "Add Filter", select the "city" field, and select "Charlestown". You can add multiple filters.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __sort__ the data based on a specific field, click the arrows next to the field name to sort in either ascending or descending order.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __hide__ columns that aren\'t relevant to you, click the blue "Hide/Unhide Columns" button at the top right of the data table, and click on the desired column names. Hidden column names will be highlighted in white. To unhide a column, simply click it again.\r\n\r\n\r\n* The Data Dictionary - which explains what each field means and what the values of each field mean - is available as a table below the directory, and is also available as a PDF under the "Data and Resources" header.\r\n\r\n\r\n* If you prefer to work with this data on your own in Microsoft Excel or another tool - you can click "Download". Any filters you apply or columns you hide will be reflected in the download.'}, 'license_title': 'Open Data Commons Public Domain Dedication and License (PDDL)', 'maintainer': None, 'classification': '9001839c-a37c-4d42-952d-6840145ab323', 'type': 'organization', 'id': '5058717c-c591-4fc1-992e-9b013978c538', 'approval_status': 'approved'}, 'name': 'zoning-board-of-appeal-tracker', 'isopen': True, 'accrual_periodicity': 'R/P1D', 'notes': '### TO VIEW A GLOSSARY OF TERMS FOR THE DIRECTORY - [CLICK HERE](https://data.boston.gov/dataset/zoning-board-of-appeal-tracker/resource/e11dcfa5-6f6f-4999-abc3-741f53c6731f)\r\n \r\n\r\n### WHAT IS THIS TRACKER FOR?\r\nThe City of Boston is committed to increasing transparency in the processes around the Zoning Board of Appeal (ZBA). The Inspectional Services Department (ISD) at the City is tasked with ensuring compliance with the zoning code. If an application for a permit is refused because of a zoning violation, applicants are able to appeal the decision to the ZBA and ask for an exception, sometimes known as a “variance.” If the ZBA grants relief, then the appellant is able to continue with the process of obtaining a permit.  \r\n\r\nIn order to provide greater transparency in the ZBA process, the City of Boston Zoning Board of Appeal tracker is now available on Analyze Boston. Each record in this tracker represents an appeal of a denied permit application; the original permit application is known as the “parent application.” To find out more information about the original permit application, visit our [Permit Finder tool](https://permitfinder.boston.gov/).  To view a map of this data, visit our [ZBA Tracker Map Tool](https://www.boston.gov/appeal-tracker).\r\n\r\n__To learn more about the ZBA process and how to file an appeal, [visit our website](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/how-file-appeal-zoning-board#start-the-appeal-process).__ \r\n   \r\n  \r\n\r\n### WHAT DOES EACH STATUS MEAN?\r\n__Appeal Submitted__ - indicates that an appeal of a zoning refusal was successfully submitted into ISD’s tracking system, either in-person at ISD (1010 Massachusetts Ave.) or through the online application portal.\r\n\r\n_More Information:_ \r\n\r\n* For detailed information on how to file an appeal, see [this page](http://boston.gov/zba-appeal) on the ISD website. \r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n\r\n* The appeal will undergo an initial review by City staff to ensure that all necessary information and \r\n    documentation has been included.\r\n* The appellant must pay a fee.\r\n  \r\n\r\n__Community Process__ - indicates that City staff have completed their review and signed off for the appeal process to move onto getting community feedback.  \r\n\r\n_Contact Information:_\r\n\r\n* Use the link below to find the Neighborhood Liaison from the Office of Neighborhood Services for the application’s location.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_    \r\n\r\n* The appellant will work with the Mayor’s [Office of Neighborhood Services](https://www.boston.gov/departments/neighborhood-services) to engage with people who own adjacent properties, members of the local community, and other relevant stakeholders.  \r\n\r\n* Depending on the type of project, the [Boston Planning and Development Agency](http://www.bostonplans.org/zoning/zoning-board-of-appeals) may also [conduct a review](http://www.bostonplans.org/getattachment/9b57370e-5a54-4d8d-b275-b93e1d7d42e1).  \r\n  \r\n \r\n__[Hearing Scheduled](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal)__ - indicates that the appeal has been scheduled for a committee or subcommittee meeting of the ZBA. For this to take place, the Mayor’s Office of Neighborhood Services has notified ISD that the appellant has adequately engaged with the community that would be affected, should the zoning relief be granted.  \r\n\r\n_Attendance Information:_\r\n\r\n* View a schedule of hearings at the ZBA [webpage](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal#UpcomingHearings). Select an Upcoming Hearing to find the list of topics and how to attend.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n \r\n* The appellant will attend the hearing in person (or through the virtual meeting). The appellant will provide the ZBA with reasons why an exception or variance to the zoning code should be granted and answer any questions from the ZBA.  \r\n\r\n* At the hearing, members of the public will be able to testify in support or against the appeal.  \r\n\r\n* The ZBA will discuss the appeal and vote to approve or deny.  \r\n\r\n_Alternatively:_  \r\n\r\n* The appellant can request a deferral; if allowed by the ZBA, during the hearing the appeal will receive a new hearing date.  \r\n\r\n* The appellant can withdraw the application; if allowed by the ZBA, it can be withdrawn without prejudice.  \r\n\r\n__Hearing Rescheduled__ - indicates that the appeal’s scheduled committee meeting has been changed. This can happen for several reasons. For example, the appellant can request a deferral if they need more time to complete or update plans, or the board can defer an appeal if a quorum isn’t present (perhaps due to a recusal). A request for deferral is approved by the board, which also selects a new hearing date.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_\r\n\r\n* Same as Hearing Scheduled above.\r\n\r\n\r\n__Hearing Concluded__ - indicates that the hearing has taken place. The appeal could have been approved, denied, deferred, or withdrawn, with or without additional requirements.  \r\n\r\n_Additional Information:_\r\n\r\n* Meeting minutes from each committee meeting are available to download from the ZBA [webpage](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal).\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n\r\n* The ZBA Executive Secretary finalizes the Board’s decision in writing or the appellant’s attorney submits a finalized decision for ISD Legal Team review.  \r\n  \r\n\r\n__[ZBA Decision Finalized](https://www.boston.gov/departments/inspectional-services/zoning-board-appeal-decisions)__ - indicates the date on the ZBA’s written decision letter. The decision is listed under the ‘result’ field.  \r\n \r\n_Next steps:_    \r\n\r\n*  Neighboring property owners are notified of the decision shortly after this date  \r\n\r\n* Beginning on the Final Decision Date, neighboring property owners and other involved parties who disagree with the ZBA’s decision have twenty days to file an appeal in Suffolk County Superior Court or Boston Housing Court. (For detailed information on the Zoning Commission and appeal process, please refer to Chapter 665 of the Acts of 1956, available [here](https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/file/2020/02/Zoning%20Commission.pdf))  \r\n  \r\n\r\n__Appeal Closed__ - indicates the appeal’s outcome has been finalized and the twenty day Appeal period has ended.\r\n\r\n_Next steps:_  \r\n\r\n* Depending on the ZBA decision, the appellant may or may not be able to continue the process for seeking the permit for which zoning relief was requested.  \r\n\r\n* If the ZBA approved or sustained with proviso, the appellant must take additional steps before continuing the permitting process.  \r\n\r\n### WHAT DOES EACH RESULT MEAN?  \r\n__Approved__ - means the zoning relief requested has been granted.  \r\n\r\n__Approved with Proviso__ - means the zoning relief requested has been granted, with some conditions that must be fulfilled before the permitting process can continue. These conditions will be detailed in the written decision of the ZBA. Examples of such conditions could include: having the Boston Planning and Development Agency review updated plans; submitting more detailed plans; or obtaining additional engineer reports.  \r\n\r\n__Denied__ - means the zoning relief requested was not granted. The appellant must wait a year before submitting a new appeal on a project for the same site.   \r\n\r\n__Denied without Prejudice__ - means the zoning relief requested was not granted. However, the appellant only has to wait thirty days before submitting an appeal on a new project at the same site.  \r\n   \r\n__Withdrawn__ - means the appellant has chosen to remove the appeal from the ZBA’s consideration. The appellant does not have to wait a year to appeal the same zoning violations.    \r\n\r\n_Note: If there is no result listed, it means that the ZBA has not issued its final written decision on the appeal. This may be the case even for appeals that have been heard by the ZBA._  \r\n \r\n\r\n### HOW DO I USE THIS TRACKER?  \r\nThis tracker is designed for members of the public and City of Boston employees to be able to quickly search for a specific appeal that has been submitted to the ZBA, or to search for appeals based on criteria such as location or primary contact, in order to identify the status of the appeal. \r\n \r\nBelow, under the "Data and Resources" header, you will see the "Zoning Board of Appeal Tracker" dataset:\r\n \r\n* To __look__ at the directory - click the "Preview" button and you will be taken to a spreadsheet-like view of the directory data.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __expand__ the number of applications available to scroll through, click the "Show _ Entries" drop down at the top left of the data table and select your desired number. Alternatively, you can scroll to the bottom right of the dataset and select your desired page number.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __search__ the tracker - use the search box to the top right of the data table to search for any keyword in the dataset. For example, if you are looking for a certain contact, type the name into the search box and see what comes back.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __filter__ the data, click the blue "Add Filter" link at the top left of the data table, select the field you would like to filter on, and select the corresponding value of that field that you would like to display. For example - if you wanted to show applications for properties in Charlestown, you would click "Add Filter", select the "city" field, and select "Charlestown". You can add multiple filters.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __sort__ the data based on a specific field, click the arrows next to the field name to sort in either ascending or descending order.\r\n\r\n\r\n* To __hide__ columns that aren\'t relevant to you, click the blue "Hide/Unhide Columns" button at the top right of the data table, and click on the desired column names. Hidden column names will be highlighted in white. To unhide a column, simply click it again.\r\n\r\n\r\n* The Data Dictionary - which explains what each field means and what the values of each field mean - is available as a table below the directory, and is also available as a PDF under the "Data and Resources" header.\r\n\r\n\r\n* If you prefer to work with this data on your own in Microsoft Excel or another tool - you can click "Download". Any filters you apply or columns you hide will be reflected in the download.', 'owner_org': '5058717c-c591-4fc1-992e-9b013978c538', 'url': '', 'license_url': 'http://www.opendefinition.org/licenses/odc-pddl', 'btype': ['tabular'], 'title': 'Zoning Board of Appeal Tracker', 'revision_id': 'bf457f19-645e-4b64-82dc-4945bdfc198d'}}
